article.headline: Washington 93, USC 82
article.story: LOS ANGELES (AP) --With Brandon Roy leading five players in double figures Washington extended its longest winning streak in five years Thursday night. Roy scored 17 points as the Huskies earned a 93-82 victory over USC in front of 3,835 at the Sports Arena. The win was the Huskies' fifth straight. Will Conroy and Mike Jensen added 16 points apiece for Washington (10-8, 5-5 Pacific-10 Conference), whose winning streak is the team's longest since 1999. "Overall, we're playing with more purpose," Huskies coach Lorenzo Romar said of the streak. "It was almost as if guys were experimenting early and said, 'Wait a minute; this isn't working. We've got to do things right." Romar believes that balanced scoring has been critical to Washington's improvement. "Some individual players have started to settle in on roles," Romar said. "When a team doesn't have to depend on one guy night in and night out, I think that makes for a good team." Desmon Farmer scored a game-high 31 points for the Trojans (9-10, 4-6), who have lost five of seven. Rory O'Neil came off the bench to score 12 points. USC held a 33-22 lead with 5:06 left in the first half when Washington used a 21-4 surge to take a 43-37 halftime lead. Roy, Jensen and Tre Simmons each scored five points during the run, as the Huskies scored all but six of their points off turnovers. The Trojans scored just one point in the final 2:40 of the half. USC cut its deficit to 70-66 after a 3-pointer from O'Neil with 8:02 to play. But Washington's Curtis Allen responded with his own 3-pointer to extend the Huskies' lead to 73-66 with 7:30 remaining.
